\f1\b\fs48 \cf0 \strokec2 Long-Term Smartphone Use, Sleep Quality, and Cardiometabolic Risk in Young Adults: A Cross-Sectional Clinical Study\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf0 Abstract\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Background:
\f0\b0  Smartphone use has become ubiquitous among young adults and is increasingly recognized as a potential contributor to sleep disturbances and adverse health outcomes. Poor sleep quality has been linked to metabolic dysregulation, increased cardiovascular risk, and impaired mental health. However, the relationship between long-term smartphone use, sleep quality, and cardiometabolic risk factors remains insufficiently explored in young adult populations.\

\f1\b Objective:
\f0\b0  To evaluate the association between smartphone use duration, sleep quality, and cardiometabolic risk markers in healthy young adults.\

\f1\b Methods:
\f0\b0  A cross-sectional study was conducted involving 310 adults aged 18\'9635 years. Smartphone usage was assessed using self-reported daily screen time and device usage logs. Sleep quality was evaluated using the Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index (PSQI). Cardiometabolic risk was assessed through anthropometric measurements, blood pressure, fasting glucose, insulin, lipid profile, and high-sensitivity C-reactive protein (hs-CRP). Multivariate regression analyses were performed to assess associations between smartphone use, sleep quality, and cardiometabolic outcomes.\

\f1\b Results:
\f0\b0  Participants with high smartphone use (>6 hours/day) demonstrated significantly poorer sleep quality compared to low-use participants (<3 hours/day) (mean PSQI score: 8.1 vs. 4.9, p < 0.001). High smartphone use was independently associated with higher body mass index, elevated fasting insulin, increased insulin resistance, and higher hs-CRP levels. Sleep quality partially mediated the relationship between smartphone use and cardiometabolic risk markers.\

\f1\b Conclusion:
\f0\b0  Excessive smartphone use is associated with poor sleep quality and early markers of cardiometabolic risk in young adults. Interventions aimed at reducing screen time and improving sleep hygiene may help mitigate long-term health risks in this population.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
