\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Introduction\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Smartphones have become an integral part of daily life, particularly among young adults. These devices facilitate communication, information access, and entertainment; however, concerns have emerged regarding their potential impact on physical and mental health. Prolonged smartphone use has been associated with sedentary behavior, disrupted circadian rhythms, sleep disturbances, and psychological stress.\
Sleep plays a critical role in metabolic regulation, cardiovascular health, and cognitive function. Poor sleep quality and insufficient sleep duration have been linked to obesity, insulin resistance, hypertension, and systemic inflammation. Young adulthood represents a critical period for the establishment of lifestyle habits that influence long-term health trajectories.\
Exposure to smartphone screens, particularly during evening hours, may disrupt sleep through several mechanisms. Blue light emitted from screens suppresses melatonin secretion, delaying sleep onset and altering circadian rhythms. Additionally, cognitive and emotional stimulation associated with smartphone content may increase arousal and impair sleep continuity.\
While previous studies have documented associations between screen time and sleep disturbances, fewer studies have examined downstream cardiometabolic consequences, particularly in otherwise healthy young adults. Understanding these relationships is important for early identification of modifiable risk factors for chronic disease.\
This study aims to investigate the association between long-term smartphone use, sleep quality, and cardiometabolic risk markers in a cohort of young adults.\
