\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Results\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 Participant Characteristics\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Of the 310 participants, 296 completed all assessments. The mean age was 24.9 \'b1 4.3 years, and 57% were female. Forty-two percent of participants were classified as high smartphone users.\
Baseline physical activity and dietary quality were similar across smartphone use groups, although high-use participants reported higher perceived stress levels.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Smartphone Use and Sleep Quality\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Mean PSQI scores increased significantly with higher smartphone use. High-use participants had a mean PSQI score of 8.1 \'b1 2.3, compared to 6.2 \'b1 2.0 in moderate users and 4.9 \'b1 1.8 in low users (p < 0.001). Poor sleep quality (PSQI >5) was observed in 72% of high users versus 28% of low users.\
Evening smartphone use was strongly correlated with prolonged sleep latency and reduced sleep duration.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Cardiometabolic Risk Markers\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 High smartphone users exhibited higher mean BMI and waist circumference compared to low-use participants. Fasting insulin levels and HOMA-IR were significantly elevated in the high-use group, indicating greater insulin resistance.\
High-use participants also demonstrated higher hs-CRP levels, suggesting increased low-grade systemic inflammation. No significant differences were observed in fasting glucose or LDL cholesterol across groups.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Multivariate and Mediation Analyses\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 After adjustment for age, sex, physical activity, diet, and stress, high smartphone use remained independently associated with poor sleep quality, higher insulin resistance, and elevated hs-CRP levels. Mediation analysis indicated that sleep quality accounted for approximately 35% of the association between smartphone use and insulin resistance.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
